For example, using 10 iterations of Newton's method, we get \begin{equation} t_0 = 0.527358354179876 \end{equation} as the maximum point.
Now, let $u=f(t)-f(t_0)$ and substitute this into the integral:
\begin{align\*}
I(x) &= \int_{-0.9}^{0.6} g(t) e^{- x f(t)} \, dt \\
&= \int_{-0.9}^{0.6} g(t) e^{- x (f(t)-f(t_0))} \, dt \\
&= \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} g(t_0+u) e^{-x u} \, du
\end{align\*}
Now, we can approximate the integral using a Gaussian integral:
\begin{equation\*}
I(x) \approx \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} g(t_0+u) e^{-x u} \, du = g(t_0) \int_{-\infty}^{\infty} e^{-x u} \, du
\end{equation\*}
